---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../components/SiteHeader.astro';
---
<Base
  title="Posts & op-eds — alexbores.io"
  description="Ideas and templates for posts and op-eds supporting Alex Bores in the NY-12 primary."
  ogUrl="https://alexbores.io/posts"
  ogType="article"
>

  <SiteHeader current="posts" breadcrumb="posts" />

  <h1 class="hero" style="font-size: clamp(30px, 4vw, 44px); margin: 0 0 16px;">Posts &amp; op-eds</h1>

  <p class="lede">
    Ideas, angles, and draft templates for writing about the NY-12 race in your own channels.
  </p>

  <div class="todo-banner">
    <strong>Work in progress.</strong> This page will collect framings, links, and short templates for different communities (EA, AI-safety, tech, personal blog, Substack, Twitter, LinkedIn). For now, a few starting points are below.
  </div>

  <section class="block">
    <p class="section-eyebrow">starting points</p>
    <h2>Angles that seem to land</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <ul>
        <li><strong>The super-PAC as the story.</strong> $10M+ from an AI-industry super-PAC attacking one state assemblyman in a primary is a remarkable escalation. Write about what that says about AI-policy politics — not about Alex specifically.</li>
        <li><strong>RAISE Act explainer.</strong> Most readers don't know what the bill does. A short, honest summary of what the law says and what the labs are pushing back against is a genuine contribution.</li>
        <li><strong>Why you personally care.</strong> First-person matters. "I work in tech / I think about AI risk / I live in NY-12 and here's what I saw in my inbox" is more persuasive than generic advocacy.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <p class="section-eyebrow">don't</p>
    <h2>A few things to avoid</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <ul>
        <li>Don't claim the effort is coordinated with the campaign — it isn't.</li>
        <li>Don't make claims about specific people's motives you can't source. The <a href="/voices">voices page</a> has citations for the factual claims used on this site.</li>
        <li>Don't imply people are bad for voting the other way. The goal is to be persuasive, not to moralize.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <p class="backlink">← <a href="/">back to alexbores.io</a></p>

  <Footer />
</Base>
